      <div type="mūlam" rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="TNV5">
      <l>iruṇilai yucci mālai vaikaṟai</l>
<l>poruṇilai yanti puṇarkkum poḻutē</l></lg>
<p xml:lang="en">The state of darkness, midday, evening, daybreak and twilight in its objective 
state<note place="foot">This is not clear to me. One could make the argument that there has been some 
distortion of standard word order for the sake of <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">etukai</hi></term>, 
in which case we could read <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">nilai poruḷ</hi></term> and understand the 
phrase to mean 'established meaning'. However, the author only applies <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">etukai</hi></term>
 sporadically. It is my impression that he simply does it where easy and unobtrusive. In this instance it would be 
 obstrusive as it would require deviating away from standard syntax. As is, I take it to mean something like real state, similarly to 
 what the phrase means in the <term xml:lang="ta">Tolkāppiyam</term> (cf. TC250.2), though what it means exactly is still not clear. 
 It could be referring to a specific time within twilight, though if so, I do not know when.</note> all together<note place="foot" xml:lang="ta">
 I am not sure what the union is here. Do these times of day connect to some elliptical object, like their respective landscapes? 
 Or are they combined with each other and as a group should be understod as <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">poḻutu</hi></q>?</note> are the times [of day].</p>
</div>
</body>
</text>
 <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition" corresp="#Ed">
    <body>
      <head xml:lang="en">Commentary</head>
      <p xml:id="TNV5comm1">e-tu. ciṟu kālamutal ām āṟuṇarttutaṉutaliṟṟu.</p>
<p xml:lang="en">The quoted [<term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">cūttiram</hi></term>] intends to make known the way in which
the minor basic time-element occurs.</p>
<p xml:id="TNV5comm2">naṭuvu paṭṭa viruḷ yāmamuṅ katir kāyum uccip poḻutu mālaip poḻutum pular kālaiyum 
antiyum ēṟpāṭu<anchor xml:id="erpatu"/> muṟaiyāṉē ain tiṇaikkum ciṟu kāla mutal ām eṉṟa vāṟu. <note>5.</note></p>
<p xml:lang="en">The middle of the dark midnight, the midday time when the sun burns, the evening-time, the time of dawn and twilight - so the basic small time-elements for the five potic landscapes occur according to the established order.</p>
      </body>
      </text>
      <standOff type="notes1" corresp="#TNV5"><note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP6i:</term> kāru mālaiyu mullai//</note>
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP7i:</term> kuṟiñci / kūtir yāma meṉmaṉār pulavar//</note>
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP8i:</term> paṉiyetir paruvamu muritteṉa moḻipa//</note>
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP9i:</term> vaikuṟu viṭiyaṉ marutam//</note> 
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP10i:</term> eṟpāṭu / neyta lātaṉ meypeṟat tōṉṟum //</note>
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP11i:</term> naṭuvunilait tiṇaiyē naṇpakala vēṉiloṭu / muṭivunilai maruṅkiṉ muṉṉiya neṟittē//</note>
<note xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Cf. TP12i:</term> piṉpaṉi tāṉu muritteṉa moḻipa</note></standOff>
<standOff type="notes4" corresp="#TNV5"><note xml:lang="en">See the note in the apparatus to TNV4.</note>
<note xml:lang="en">It is also worth pointing out that the TNV only lists five time of days, whereas the TP gives six - both <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">vaikarai</hi></term> ('early dawn') and <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">viṭiyal</hi></term> ('late dawn') are approriate in <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">marutam</hi></term>.</note></standOff>
