<standOff type="notes4" corresp="#TNV5comm2"><note xml:lang="en" target="#erpatu">I have deviated away 
from the MS reading because I find the required combination of an <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">-um</hi></term> particle 
with a subsequent <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">-ē</hi></term> particle difficult. This is not documented in the Caṅkam
 corpus. Were it not for this, <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">muṟpāṭu muṟaiyāṉe</hi></q> would have been perfectly fine - 'according to the earlier order'. 
 I was not convinced by U.Vē.Cā.'s interpretation. Based his corrections to the copy of the MS which he originally made, 
 I believe he decided against teh MS reading for a similar reason to me. Why he emended to <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">eṟpāṭu</hi></q> ('afternoon', 'sunrise'), I am not sure.
  The creates a six-fold enumeration where in the <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">cūttiram</hi></term> 5 times are listed. This is in itself is not a terminal fault,
  especially considering the TP lists six times and that <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">eṟpāṭu</hi></q> could correspond to to 
  <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">viṭiyal</hi></q> ('late dawn'), found in TP9i (see note to TNV5). However, this would be out of place
   in the enumeration found here in the commentary. For this to make sense, one would need it to be placed next to <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">pular kālai</hi></q> ('dawn'). 
   As seen in the commentary to the previous <term xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">cūttiram</hi></term>, when the commentator uses <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">muṟaiyāṉē</hi></q>, 
   he is stating that the order of the items in his enumeration, follow that of the <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">aintiṇai</hi></q> in
   the commentary to TNV3. My solution is to read <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">ēṟpāṭu</hi></q> ('system, established custom') which qualifies <q xml:lang="ta"><hi rend="italic">muṟaiyāṉē</hi></q>. 
   This then means something like 'in the established order'. This is the least invasive emendation of the MS text that makes sense.</note></standOff>
